version: 1
display_name: 'VCFK-9X-000043 - The VMware Cloud Foundation vCenter Envoy service''s configuration must be protected from unauthorized modification.'
global_description: |-
  As a rule, accounts on a server are to be kept to a minimum. The resources to which these accounts have access must also be closely monitored and controlled. Only the system administrator needs access to all the system's capabilities and the server configuration files.
osfinger:
  - VMware Photon OS-5
refs:
  disa_stig:
    - VCFK-9X-000043
  srg:
    - SRG-APP-000211-WSR-000030
  cci:
    - CCI-001082
    - CCI-001813
    - CCI-002235
  nist:
    - AC-6 (10)
    - CM-5 (1) (a)
    - SC-2
benchmark_id:
  vcf9_vcenter_envoy:
    type: custom
    desc: 'The VMware Cloud Foundation vCenter Envoy service''s configuration must be protected from unauthorized modification.'
    control_id: VCFK-9X-000043
    scored: true
    profile:
      - default
    information: |-
      At a command prompt, validate the vCenter Envoy service's configuration is secure by running the following:

      # find /etc/vmware-envoy/ /etc/vmware-envoy-hgw/ /etc/vmware-envoy-sidecar/ /etc/vmware-envoy-system-proxy/ -xdev -type f -a '(' -perm -o+w -o -not -user root -o -not -group root ')' -exec ls -ld {} \;

      If any files are returned, this is a finding.
    rationale: |-
      As a rule, accounts on a server are to be kept to a minimum. The resources to which these accounts have access must also be closely monitored and controlled. Only the system administrator needs access to all the system's capabilities and the server configuration files.
    remediation: |-
      At the command prompt, correct permissions for Envoy configuration files by running the following:

      # chmod o-w <file>
      # chown root:root <file>
